Acknowledgments and Intellectual Heritage
-----------------------------------------

The Clef language and the Fidelity Framework build upon ideas, research, and
open-source contributions from many projects and communities. We gratefully
acknowledge the following:

LANGUAGE DESIGN HERITAGE

  F# Programming Language (MIT License)
  https://github.com/dotnet/fsharp
  https://fsharp.org/specs/language-spec/
  Clef's syntax, type system, and functional programming model descend
  directly from F#, which itself inherits from OCaml and the ML family.

  F* (FStar) Proof-Oriented Programming Language (Apache 2.0)
  https://github.com/FStarLang/FStar
  https://fstar-lang.org/
  F*'s approach to refinement types, effect systems, and proof-oriented
  programming deeply influenced Clef's verification architecture and
  the Fidelity Framework's proof-aware compilation model.

COMPILER INFRASTRUCTURE

  LLVM and MLIR (Apache 2.0 with LLVM Exception)
  https://llvm.org/
  https://mlir.llvm.org/
  The Composer compiler targets MLIR as its intermediate representation.
  MLIR's multi-level dialect system is foundational to Clef's approach
  to progressive lowering and hardware-aware code generation.

  Nanopass Compiler Framework
  https://nanopass.org/
  A. Keep and R. K. Dybvig, "A Nanopass Infrastructure for Compiler
  Education," Proc. ACM SIGPLAN ICFP, 2013.
  The nanopass approach to compiler construction — decomposing compilation
  into many small, composable passes — influenced the design of Composer's
  compilation pipeline and the Program Semantic Graph architecture.

THEORETICAL FOUNDATIONS

  Coeffects: A Calculus of Context-Dependent Computation
  T. Petricek, D. Orchard, and A. Mycroft, ACM SIGPLAN Notices 49.9, 2014.
  The formal foundation for Clef's coeffect system, which tracks what
  computations require from their execution context.

  Koka: Programming with Row Polymorphic Effect Types
  D. Leijen, EPTCS 153, 2014.
  Koka's algebraic effect system influenced Clef's approach to
  effect tracking and compiler-driven optimization.

  SSA is Functional Programming
  A. W. Appel, ACM SIGPLAN Notices 33.4, 1998.
  The equivalence between SSA form and functional programming established
  by Appel enables the dual control-flow/data-flow interpretation central
  to the Program Semantic Graph.

  Delimited Continuations
  O. Danvy and A. Filinski, "Abstracting Control," LFP, 1990.
  The theoretical foundation for zero-copy async and WAMI's stack
  switching implementation.

ECOSYSTEM

  Hextra Hugo Theme (MIT License)
  https://github.com/imfing/hextra
  This site is built with the Hextra theme for Hugo.

